Challenge:

#writeups/akaCTF #writeups/2024 #writeups/Misc #writeups/easy

Solves: 84/696
Points: 100
Skills: #writeups/python #writeups/Docker #writups/linux

  • We are given 2 files: chall.py & DockerFile
About Docker
  • When I began this challenge, I knew very little about docker or how to use it. Often with simple stuff like this I would cope and just work around it because I didn't want to spend time getting it setup and working.
    • But it is super important that you learn it like i did during this ctf! I will explain Docker later!
  • General Overview: You are given a Netcat command or a IP:Port like shown: 20.80.240.190:4449
    • This normally means that in order to get the real flag, you will need to access their device at that IP address on the open port given.
    • This can be done using the netcat command: nc IPAddress Port (nc 20.80.240.190 4449)
    • The other files given are so that you can test out your exploit locally with the same exact files as what is on there device so that you dont DOS there devices.
      • You are not given the real flag for your local environment, so you will often have to make your own fake flag or they will give you a dummy flag for local testing.
      • Dockerfiles are great for this because it creates a Docker image which creates Docker Containers which are isolated environments that can run the files given with no issues!
  • Now Given that you understand generally what your given and why, We can take a quick look at the files to get a general understanding of what is going on. I opened the files using neovim text editor:
  • The code is pretty simple, but there can be some small things that can be missed without further analysis!
    • Use AI to get a linebyline general explanation of the code.
    • And for a more detailed understanding, use the python docs.
  • Unless you instantly know the exploit, we should probably look over at the DockerFile and try to get this setup for proper local environment use!

Aside On Docker

  • Vocabulary:
    • Docker: A package or application that manages Docker containers and build Docker Files.
    • DockerFile: A set of Instructions for Docker to build a Docker Image.
    • Docker Image: A lightweight executable package which includes everthing needed to run a piece of software or code.
    • Docker Container: A running instance of a docker image in an Isolated Environment.

  • You will need to install the Docker package to build the DockerFile.

    • Most distributions have unofficial packages that use different functionality. Follow the Docker Engine installation instructions to get it properly installed on your system!
      Important

      Docker Is a Service and needs to be started to work!

      • sudo systemctl docker start

  • Once the Service is started, move into the directory where the DockerFile and python file is located.

    • Run: docker build -t imageName .
      • -t: means your taging the image with a name.
      • ".": is the current Directory where the DockerFile is located.
    Build Error
    • You likely will get a build error. This is because the DockerFile is looking for a file in the current directory called flag.txt. Remember what I said at the beginning, This is supposed to be the flag on the server that you want to get!
    • Create a dummy flag.txt file in the current directory and add a dummy flag in the content like this: akaCTF{light_work_no_reaction}. Now run the build command again!
    Attention
    • The build command doesnt add or modify anything in the current directory!
    • It just builds an image and stores it in Docker Storage: For linux (/var/lib/docker)

  • Images can be managed using these commands:

    • docker images: Lists the images built
    • docker rmi image_id: Remove an image based on ID found using previous command

  • Next you need to Run an Image aka Create a Docker Container for that Image.

    • docker run imageName: Creates a container with a random ID
      • Note this command doesn't work for most CTF containers which are meant to simulate connecting to a remote server which you need to interact with. I will show the proper command in the next section.
        Container Management
        • You can create multiple containers of the same Image, so only execute the run command once.
    • Use these commands to manage the containers:
      • docker ps: Shows running containers.
      • docker ps -a: Shows all containers including stopped containers.
      • docker stop container_ID: Stops the container, Doesn't Delete It!
        • When you leave a container using ctrl-C, the container is stopped not removed!

  • Proper Run command to Create a Working Container!

    • docker run -d -p localPort:containerPort imageName
      • -p: Set up a portToport connection between your computer and the open port in the container
      • -d: Detach process from the terminal so you can continue using the terminal.
        How to know what port is open on the container?
        • It is in the bottom line of the DockerFile:
        • CMD socat -T120 TCP-L: 4444: Tells you that it will listen (TCP-L) for a data on port 4444 for 120 seconds (-T120) before shutting off the connection.
          • Once data is sent it will execute this command: (EXEC: "python3 chally.py"), which will run the program you will exploit.
      • When choosing your localPort, choose values above 1024 and less than 65535 because these ports are not commonly used by other applications.
    Example
    • docker run -p 8080:4444 pyJail

  • Now use Netcat like for the real challenge to connect to the container. Remember that Netcats sytax is: nc IPAddress Port.

    • The address is our own computer (localhost)since the container is connected to our local port. and the port is the local port on our computer we put it as (8080).
    • Connect: nc localhost 8080
      • You only need to Create the container once, since when the program fails it just stops the container and doesnt remove it. To start the container just Netcat onto the container!

Code Analysis & Research:

  • Finally, you can now attempt to exploit the ctf locally. That may have seemed like a lot but it is just a lot to learn, not to do! Practice makes perfect! I learned it during the CTF ahhah!
  • I began by studying the code line by line to understand possible areas for exploitation as well as trying to figure out what the challenge is trying to get you to do. Here is the code with commits to add context and information.
import sys #import library that might have stuff to use to expoit!
from string import printable # Important function that defines a specific set of 
# characters. Here is the set: 
# [abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ0123456789!"#$%&'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\]^_`{|}~]
# And All kinds of whitespace: space, tab, linefeed, return, formfeed, vertical tab.

print('''
#################################################################
#                                                               #
#   Welcome to pyJail!                                          #
#                                                               #
#   You have been jailed for using too many characters.         #
#                                                               #
#   You are only allowed to use 16 characters of printable      #
#   ascii.                                                      #
#                                                               #
#   If you manage to break free, you will get the flag.         #
#                                                               #
#################################################################\n''')

code = input('> ') # User input that gets put into the code varible.

sys.stdin = None # Disables stdin library from sys which might limit the possible expoits.

len = sum(1 for char in code if char in printable)
# Adds up each char in the input varible only if it is considered "printable".
# Printable is shown above!

if len >= 17: # Limits the len of our input varible to 16... But that is if it gets counted as printable!
    print('Too long!') # Output when input is over 16 char.
    exit() # Leaves program.
                                                                                                   
eval(code) # Command that runns any other command given to its input!!!!!!!!
  • During the ctf it is important to understand code in depth before trying to solve the challenge. I made the mistake of not doing this during the ctf and wasted a lot of time trying for stuff that makes no sense.

Pit Falls:

  1. Trying to use commands that rely on stdin to escape the pyJail.
    • This doesnt work because the stdin is disabled! Seems obvious but yet i still tried it because it didn't fully understand the code!
      Example
      • Using the help() command can be used to then print the flag. But stdin is disabled after the initial input, so you just get an error the second you open help().
  2. Trying to use libraries that didn't exist.
    • During CTFs you will try anything, which is okay. But a lot of the time, its a waste of time, understand the code first to then create an attack plan.
    • Note: There are ways to get around this, but for looking for a basic solution when your new to pyjails; These solutions don't come to mind without a cheat sheet.
  3. Trying to use just the open() command by itself.
    • Simple mistake, open command just creates a file object for python then to interact with.
    • Additional commands are needed to read or output the data within the file.
    • Again do your research first or use AI to help you if you don't understand something.

Finding the Key:

  • After messing around and making a ton of mistakes, I wanted to go more in depth into the relationship between the fact that the payload needs to be less than 17 "printable" characters.
    - This implies that if the characters were not "printable" then they would get past the length check.
    Research
    • After some research, I found an older ctf where they used italicized characters to get past an ascii filter.
    • So I tested out spamming an italicized 'a' 25 times and i got an error instead of a "length is to long" output!
  • Once I realized I could bypass the length check using italicized characters, I knew I just needed a payload that could output me the flag!
    • I know that the file with the flag is located in the same directory has the python script I am trying to escape because of the DockerFile:
      • The "./" puts both files within the current working directory!
    • So if I can just open and read flag.txt or open a shell to then output the contents?

Solution:

Research
  • I found a pyJail cheat-sheet online which gives me many possible payloads
    • You could have went straight here from the beginning and find out about the italics exploit, but being able to come to certain conclusions about the CTF using your own knowledge and problem solving skills is more important.
    • Once you understand what needs to get done, there isn't anything wrong trying to find payloads from there since you know what kind of payload to look for!
  • We want a payload that can use italics, no stdin, uses less than 16 printable chars since some chars can not be italized such as ()."'[] and any command that needs to be proccessed by operating system underneath such as the file name. (Italics Converter)
  • Even with the cheat-sheet, So few of the payloads work! After a bunch of testing, here is a bunch that almost work and some that work:(Other Good Cheat-Sheet)
    • 𝘦𝘹𝘪𝘵(*𝘰𝘱𝘦𝘯("flag.txt")) => exit command will output file to console after leaving pyJail because "*" unpacks the file!
    • 𝘰𝘱𝘦𝘯("flag.txt").𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘥() => Fails because Information goes to console but your still stuck in the pyJail!
    • 𝘴𝘺𝘴.𝘮𝘰𝘥𝘶𝘭𝘦𝘴["os"].𝘴𝘺𝘴𝘵𝘦𝘮("ls") => Executes command "ls", but we need flag and cat command is too long and will cause too long of a payload. So use sh which pops a shell!!!
    • 𝘴𝘺𝘴.𝘮𝘰𝘥𝘶𝘭𝘦𝘴["os"].𝘴𝘺𝘴𝘵𝘦𝘮("sh") => Now you can use any linux commands to open flag.txt
    • 𝘣𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘬𝘱𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘵() => Fails due to using stdin
    • help() => Fails due to using stdin
    • system("cat /flag") => Longer than 16 printable chars + system() only works in python2.7
    • 𝘴𝘺𝘴𝘵𝘦𝘮("cat /flag") => Italics "system" causes error in python
    • 𝘰𝘴.𝘱𝘰𝘱𝘦𝘯("ls").𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘥() => os library is not imported int he python env.
Important

Notice how a lot of simple payloads don't work and that understanding the code and what kind of payload is needed is extremely important!!

  • Go use a working payload on the actual machine instead of locally to get the flag! It should work the same as it does locally since you setup the Docker properly! (nc 20.80.240.190 4449)
